('Cat-Cow Breath Flow',
 'erectors', array['core','hip_flexors'], array['erectors','core'],
 'yoga_pilates', 'rotation', array['yoga_mat'], 'beginner', false,
 'On hands and knees. Inhale: drop the belly, lift the chest and tailbone (cow — spinal extension). Exhale: round the spine toward the ceiling, tuck the chin and tailbone (cat — spinal flexion). Flow between with the breath for 5-10 rounds.',
 'Moving without the breath (the breath drives the movement in cat-cow — moving independently of breath defeats the therapeutic value), making the movements too small (full range of spinal flexion and extension is the goal).',
 'yoga',
 array['Breath leads: inhale starts the extension, exhale starts the flexion — the body follows the breath','Maximum range: at cat, imagine the spine is a drawbridge lifting to the ceiling. At cow, let it bow completely toward the floor','This is one of the best morning practices: it lubricates the intervertebral discs and wakes the spine after a night of compression','5-10 slow rounds is enough: this is a preparation and transition pose, not a long hold pose'],
 array['Thread the Needle from Cat-Cow','Extended Cat-Cow with Hip Circles'],
 array['Child''s Pose','Seated Spinal Circles'],
