('Pilates Hundred',
 'core', array['hip_flexors','rectus_abdominis'], array['core','hip_flexors'],
 'yoga_pilates', 'isometric', array['yoga_mat'], 'beginner', false,
 'Lie on back. Lift legs to tabletop (90°) or 45°. Curl the head and shoulders off the mat. Extend arms parallel to the floor. Pump the arms vigorously up and down in small beats: 5 pumps on the inhale, 5 on the exhale. Complete 100 pumps.',
 'Holding the breath (must maintain the 5-5 breathing rhythm throughout), straining the neck (the head stays lifted but the neck relaxes — the lift comes from the thoracic spine, not the neck), legs sagging toward the floor.',
 'pilates',
 array['5 short inhales, 5 short exhales: the rhythmic breathing is as important as the arm pumps','Legs at 45° is harder than tabletop: only go to 45° if you can maintain a flat lower back — if the back arches, keep the legs higher','The Hundred develops thoracic flexion strength, hip flexor control, and rhythmic breathing simultaneously — the foundational Pilates exercise','The 100 pumps (100 arm beats) is precise: this is not approximately 100'],
 array['Hundreds with Straight Legs Low','Hundreds with Resistance Band'],
 array['Hundreds at Tabletop','Hundreds with Bent Knees on Floor'],
