 'Lie on back, arms pressed into the mat. Bring legs over the head (like rollover). Then press the legs vertically to the ceiling, lifting the hips from the mat. Hold 3 breaths. Slowly lower back through rollover to flat. Repeat 5 times.',
 'Bending the knees (legs must stay straight throughout), not pressing the arms into the floor for support (this is essential for spinal control), using momentum to swing into the inversion.',
 'pilates',
 array['The jackknife reverses the roll-over: legs go overhead, then VERTICALLY to ceiling — this is the sequence','Arms actively pressing into the mat: think of pushing the mat away — this creates the support that makes spinal articulation possible','This exercise is the Pilates equivalent of a full inversion: it builds both spinal articulation and hamstring flexibility simultaneously','Contraindication: do not do this if the rollover creates neck or head pressure — modify with legs at 45° only'],
