 'Lie on your side with hips stacked, knees bent to 90°. Keep the feet together. Rotate the top knee toward the ceiling as far as possible while keeping the feet together (like a clamshell opening). Lower with control. 10-15 reps each side.',
 'Rocking the pelvis backward to gain more range (the pelvis must stay absolutely still — any rocking is hip rotation, not glute medius work), separating the feet (the feet stay together as an anchor).',
 'pilates',
 array['Feet together, always: the feet-together position is the cue that forces the rotation to come from the hip, not the foot','Pelvis still: place a hand on the top hip — it must not move AT ALL as the knee rises','This is the safest possible glute medius exercise: no load, no standing, no balance challenge','Rehabilitation staple: this exercise is prescribed by physiotherapists for hip instability, PFPS, IT band syndrome, and lower back pain'],
