('Thoracic Spine Rotation (Quadruped)',
 'thoracic_erectors', array['obliques','rhomboids'], array['thoracic_erectors','obliques'],
 'mobility', 'rotation', array['yoga_mat'], 'beginner', false,
 'Start on hands and knees. Place one hand behind the head. Rotate the elbow toward the floor, then open toward the ceiling. Repeat 10 times each side. Keep the lower back still — all rotation from the upper back.',
 'Rotating from the hips and lower back (the lower body must remain completely still — only the thoracic spine rotates), not following the elbow with the eyes (the eyes drive the cervical rotation which extends the thoracic rotation).',
 'mobility',
 array['Eyes follow the elbow: wherever the elbow goes, the eyes track — this connects cervical and thoracic rotation for maximum range','Lower body static: from the hips down, nothing moves. From the hips up, maximum rotation','Open toward the ceiling: at the end of the rotation, reach the elbow as high as possible to find the ceiling','Thoracic rotation reduces with age and desk work faster than almost any other movement quality — daily practice is the only solution'],
 array['Thoracic Rotation Standing','Thoracic Rotation with Foam Roller'],
 array['Seated Thoracic Rotation','Gentle Shoulder Blade Squeeze'],
 array['mobility','thoracic_spine','rotation','posture','daily_routine'],
 array['acute_thoracic_injuries','vertebral_fractures'],
 'mixed', 'transverse', true, 2, 10, null, 10, true),

('Ankle Dorsiflexion Mobility',
 'calves', array['Achilles_tendon','peroneals','tibialis_anterior'], array['calves','Achilles_tendon'],
 'mobility', 'stretch', array['yoga_mat','wall'], 'beginner', false,
 'Kneel with toes against a wall. Drive the knee forward over the toes toward the wall as far as possible without the heel lifting. Measure how far the knee travels past the toes. 10 reps each side, then hold the end range for 30 seconds.',
 'Letting the heel lift (the heel MUST stay on the floor — if it lifts, the calf is winning and the joint is not mobilizing), not going to the wall (must use a wall or physical reference to measure and progressively improve the range).',
 'mobility',
 array['Knee to wall: the distance from toe to wall when the knee just touches the wall is your ankle dorsiflexion measure','Heel stays down: any heel rise means you''ve run out of available ankle range — build up to more range over weeks','Ankle dorsiflexion directly limits squat depth: if the heels lift in a squat, this is almost always the limiting factor','Normal: 10-12cm of knee travel past the toes. Less than 9cm indicates a significant restriction requiring daily mobility work'],
 array['Ankle Dorsiflexion with Band Distraction','Weighted Dorsiflexion Squat'],
 array['Ankle Alphabet','Standing Calf Stretch'],
 array['mobility','ankle','dorsiflexion','squat_prep','runners'],
