('Shoulder CARs (Controlled Articular Rotation)',
 'deltoids', array['rotator_cuff','serratus','trapezius'], array['deltoids','rotator_cuff'],
 'mobility', 'rotation', array['yoga_mat'], 'beginner', false,
 'Stand with the arm at the side. Slowly move the arm through the largest possible circle the shoulder joint can make — forward, up, back, down — at maximum speed control. 3 slow circles each direction each side. No compensation from the spine.',
 'Compensating with the thoracic spine or trunk (the ball of the shoulder must do all the work — if the torso moves, reduce the range until it doesn''t), rushing the movement, not going to the actual end range in each direction.',
 'mobility',
 array['CARs are controlled articular rotations from Functional Range Conditioning: the premise is to move the joint through its full range under nervous system control','Maximum tension throughout: this is not a relaxed swing — actively squeeze every muscle group that surrounds the joint at each point in the rotation','Three planes, one circle: the shoulder circles through flexion, horizontal flexion, extension, horizontal extension — use each plane deliberately','Daily CARs maintain joint health: the synovial fluid that lubricates the joint is produced by movement — immobility reduces this production'],
 array['Shoulder CARs Loaded','Shoulder PAILS/RAILS'],
 array['Arm Circles','Pendulum Shoulder Swings'],
 array['mobility','FRC','shoulder_health','daily_routine','joint_health'],
