('Jefferson Curl',
 'erectors', array['hamstrings','glutes'], array['erectors','hamstrings'],
 'mobility', 'stretch', array['bodyweight','barbell','dumbbells'], 'advanced', false,
 'Stand on a step or elevated surface. Hold a light weight (or bodyweight only). Slowly curl the spine forward vertebra by vertebra — chin first, then neck, then upper back, then lower back, then hips hinge — until hanging. Reverse to stand. 5-8 reps.',
 'Moving too quickly and losing the vertebral articulation (this is the slowest, most controlled spinal movement in existence), using too much weight before the back muscles have adequate eccentric strength, attempting this without years of strength training experience.',
 'mobility',
 array['Vertebra by vertebra: the Jefferson curl is the physical embodiment of spinal articulation — feel each vertebra separate as you curl','This is the ONLY loaded spinal flexion exercise: it is controversial but the evidence supports it for building disc resilience when progressed appropriately','Start with bodyweight: add weight (a 5kg plate) only after months of practice with bodyweight and only under coach supervision','The reverse: roll back up in the same deliberate sequence — from the lumbar up through the thoracic to the cervical'],
 array['Jefferson Curl with Added Weight','Jefferson Curl at Greater Range'],
 array['Hanging Spinal Decompression','Cat-Cow Breath Flow'],
 array['mobility','spine','advanced','FRC','erectors'],
 array['acute_disc_herniation','osteoporosis','acute_lower_back_injury','beginning_strength_trainees'],
