('Frog Pose Groin Stretch',
 'groin', array['hip_flexors','inner_thighs','hip_adductors'], array['groin','hip_flexors','inner_thighs'],
 'mobility', 'stretch', array['yoga_mat'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Start on hands and knees. Walk the knees as wide as possible, keeping the feet in line with the knees. Lower onto the forearms if comfortable. Rock forward and back slightly to find the deepest point. Hold 2-3 minutes.',
 'Knees wider than the feet (must maintain 90° alignment between thigh and shin), forcing the range too aggressively, rounding the upper back while on forearms.',
 'mobility',
 array['Ankles in line with knees: as the knees widen, the feet widen to match — maintaining the 90° angle protects the knee','Neutral spine: even in this position, the back should be relatively flat — resist the natural tendency to round','Shift forward slightly to increase the stretch, backward to reduce it — find the edge of productive sensation','The frog stretch accesses the hip adductor group (groin) that almost no other exercise can reach effectively'],
 array['Advanced Frog with Hip Circles','Weighted Frog Stretch'],
 array['Supported Frog (With Blocks)','Standing Groin Stretch'],
 array['mobility','groin','inner_thighs','hip_adductors','sports_specific'],
 array['hip_replacement','acute_groin_injury','knee_injuries_severe'],
 'isometric', 'frontal', false, 1, null, 120, 10, true),

('Half Kneeling Ankle Mobility',
 'calves', array['Achilles_tendon','tibialis_anterior'], array['calves','Achilles_tendon'],
 'mobility', 'stretch', array['yoga_mat','wall'], 'beginner', false,
 'Kneel with one foot forward, toes against the wall. Lean the knee toward the wall while keeping the heel down. Drive the knee as far sideways past the big toe as possible. 15 reps each foot.',
 'Not keeping the heel flat (any heel lift means the stretch has been lost), not going laterally (driving the knee over the big toe accesses different ankle restriction than a straight-forward drive), too slow between reps.',
 'mobility',
 array['Drive the knee laterally: past the outside edge of the little toe — this accesses the talo-crural joint (true ankle joint) in a different plane','15 reps: the repetitions create synovial fluid production and tissue heating that static holds cannot replicate','Lateral drive for ankle, forward drive for Achilles: train both directions to mobilize both components of ankle restriction','Every squat, lunge, and hinge pattern is downstream of ankle mobility — this is the highest-leverage lower body mobility exercise'],
 array['Ankle Mobility with Band Distraction','Loaded Ankle Mobility'],
 array['Seated Ankle Circles','Ankle Alphabet'],
 array['mobility','ankle','squat_prep','functional','daily_routine'],
 array['acute_ankle_injuries','Achilles_tendon_rupture','ankle_fusion'],
 'push', 'multi', true, 2, 15, null, 10, true),

('Wrist Circles and Mobility',
 'forearms', array['wrist_extensors','wrist_flexors'], array['forearms'],
 'mobility', 'rotation', array['yoga_mat'], 'beginner', false,
 'Extend arms in front. Make fists. Circle the wrists slowly through full range: 10 clockwise, 10 counter-clockwise each wrist. Follow with wrist flexion and extension (prayer position, reverse prayer). Hold each end position 20 seconds.',
 'Moving only through comfortable range (the mobility exercise requires moving to the edges of uncomfortable range — never painful, always slightly challenging), moving too quickly.',
 'mobility',
 array['End range: the point where you feel mild tension — that is where mobility is gained','Both directions: clockwise and counter-clockwise — different muscles and joint surfaces are challenged in each direction','Prayer and reverse prayer: pressing both palms together in front tests wrist extension; reverse (back of hands together) tests flexion','Wrist health is critical for push-up, plank, yoga, and gymnastics athletes — daily wrist mobility prevents carpal tunnel and tendinitis'],
 array['Wrist Weight-Bearing Circles','Loaded Wrist Mobility'],
 array['Wrist Alphabet','Seated Wrist Stretches'],
 array['mobility','wrist_health','warm_up','daily_routine','prevention'],
 array['acute_wrist_injuries','carpal_tunnel_severe'],
 'mixed', 'multi', false, 1, null, 120, 10, true),

('Prone Hip Internal Rotation',
 'piriformis', array['glutes','IT_band','hip_external_rotators'], array['piriformis','glutes'],
 'mobility', 'rotation', array['yoga_mat'], 'beginner', false,
 'Lie face down with both knees bent at 90°, feet pointing to the ceiling. Allow the feet to drop outward (hip internal rotation). Hold 2-3 minutes. Progress: actively push the feet further outward.',
 'Allowing the lower back to arch (must maintain neutral spine — a small rolled towel under the lower belly helps), only doing external rotation (internal rotation is far more restricted in most people and receives far less attention).',
 'mobility',
 array['Most athletes have adequate external rotation but significant internal rotation restrictions: this directly addresses the more neglected pattern','Relax completely: the passive version (just letting the feet fall) develops flexibility; the active version (pushing the feet outward) develops strength in the new range','This position reveals dramatic side-to-side differences: a 20°+ asymmetry warrants physiotherapy assessment','Hip internal rotation restriction is implicated in lower back pain, knee pain (PFPS), and hamstring injury risk — it is a critical diagnostic stretch'],
 array['Active Hip Internal Rotation','Hip IR with Resistance Band'],
 array['Figure-4 Stretch','Supine Hip Rotation'],
 array['mobility','hip_internal_rotation','piriformis','assessment','injury_prevention'],
 array['hip_replacement','acute_hip_injuries','piriformis_syndrome_acute'],
 'isometric', 'transverse', true, 1, null, 120, 10, true),

('Seated Hip External Rotation (Figure-4)',
 'piriformis', array['glutes','IT_band'], array['piriformis','glutes'],
 'mobility', 'stretch', array['bodyweight','chair'], 'beginner', false,
 'Sit in a chair. Cross one ankle over the opposite knee in a figure-4 shape. Gently press down on the bent knee. Optional: lean forward from the hips. Hold 2-3 minutes each side.',
 'Rounding the back to lean forward (hip hinge — not spine rounding — creates the stretch), pressing too hard on the knee (the pressure should be a gentle nudge, not a forceful push).',
 'mobility',
 array['Seated version is the accessible version of pigeon pose: suitable for beginners, seniors, and workplace stretching','Lean forward from the hips: once the figure-4 is established, hinging forward from the hips dramatically increases the piriformis stretch','The knee nudge helps: a gentle downward pressure on the bent knee opens the hip further — but only nudge, never force','Daily practice for desk workers: do this in an office chair for 2 minutes each side — it counteracts the hip compression of sitting'],
 array['Supine Figure-4 (Greater Range)','Pigeon Pose'],
 array['Simple Crossed Leg Sit','Standing Hip External Rotation'],
 array['mobility','piriformis','sciatic_relief','seated','daily_routine'],
 array['hip_replacement','acute_hip_injuries','knee_injuries_that_prevent_crossing'],
 'isometric', 'multi', true, 1, null, 120, 10, true),

('Lacrosse Ball Glute Release',
 'glutes', array['piriformis','IT_band'], array['glutes','piriformis'],
 'mobility', 'stretch', array['lacrosse_ball','foam_roller'], 'beginner', false,
 'Sit on a lacrosse ball placed under one glute. Shift weight to find a tender spot. Cross the ankle over the knee (figure-4) to increase the tension. Hold each spot for 60-90 seconds. Cover the entire glute, then the piriformis (deeper, more medial).',
 'Moving too quickly between spots (must hold each spot for 60-90 seconds — the myofascial release requires time and sustained pressure), using a too-soft foam roller (lacrosse ball provides the focal pressure needed for deep glute work).',
 'mobility',
 array['Find the spot, then hold: this is not a rolling technique — it is sustained pressure release','The figure-4 increases the tension: crossing the ankle over the knee while applying pressure dramatically intensifies the piriformis release','The ''sweet spot'' is just lateral to the sacrum: this is where the piriformis attaches and where most piriformis-related sciatica originates','Breathe into the spot: the pressure-pain paradox of myofascial release resolves with sustained breath — the tension will soften within 60-90 seconds'],
 array['Lacrosse Ball Deep Tissue Full Session','Lacrosse Ball Hip Flexor'],
 array['Foam Roller Glutes','Supine Figure-4 Stretch'],
 array['mobility','glute_release','myofascial','recovery','sciatic_relief'],
 array['acute_muscle_tears','bruising_severe','skin_injuries_in_area'],
 'isometric', 'multi', true, 1, null, 90, 10, true),

('Foam Roller Thoracic Extension',
 'erectors', array['pectorals','rhomboids','thoracic_spine'], array['erectors','pectorals'],
 'mobility', 'extension', array['foam_roller'], 'beginner', false,
 'Place the foam roller perpendicular to the spine, across the upper-to-mid back. Support the head with the hands. Gently extend over the roller. Move the roller one segment at a time down the spine, from the shoulder blades to the lower thoracic. Do NOT roll the lumbar spine.',
 'Rolling the lumbar spine (the foam roller must not go below the last rib — lumbar extension on a foam roller is not safe), moving too quickly (spend 30-60 seconds at each spinal segment), not supporting the head.',
 'mobility',
 array['Each thoracic segment: position, extend, breathe in and out 3-5 times, move down one segment','Stop at the ribs: the last rib marks the boundary between thoracic (safe for foam roller extension) and lumbar (unsafe)','Head supported throughout: interlace the fingers behind the head — this ensures the neck is never strained by the extension','This undoes the forward-rounded posture of desk work, driving, and device use — one of the most beneficial daily practices available'],
 array['Foam Roller Thoracic Extension with Arm Reach','Foam Roller Thoracic Extension Long Hold'],
 array['Thoracic Extension Over Chair','Cat-Cow Thoracic Focus'],
 array['mobility','thoracic','posture','foam_rolling','recovery'],
 array['acute_thoracic_injury','vertebral_fractures','osteoporosis_severe'],
 'push', 'sagittal', false, 1, null, 120, 10, true),

('Overhead Shoulder Stretch (Lat Doorway)',
 'lats', array['teres_major','posterior_deltoid','serratus'], array['lats','teres_major'],
 'mobility', 'stretch', array['bodyweight','doorway'], 'beginner', false,
 'Stand in a doorway. Place one hand on the doorframe at shoulder height. Step through the doorway, rotating the body away from the arm. Feel the stretch along the lat and underarm area. Hold 30-60 seconds each side.',
 'Rounding the shoulder (keep it packed — the arm should feel long, not hunched), rushing the rotation (the stretch deepens gradually — hold the position and breathe).',
 'mobility',
 array['The lat is the muscle that most limits overhead mobility: tight lats prevent full arm raise and contribute to shoulder impingement','Step through slowly: the rotation of the body away from the fixed arm is what creates the stretch — don''t just lean','Breathe into the side body: on each exhale, the lat releases slightly further','For overhead athletes (volleyball, swimming, cricket), this is the most important daily stretch for injury prevention'],
 array['Lat Stretch with Band','Active Lat Stretch'],
 array['Child''s Pose Arms Forward','Overhead Reach with Support'],
 array['mobility','lats','overhead_mobility','shoulder_health','sports_specific'],
 array['shoulder_injuries_acute','rotator_cuff_tears_acute'],
 'pull', 'frontal', true, 2, null, 40, 10, true),

('Pec Minor Stretch',
 'pectorals', array['anterior_deltoid','serratus'], array['pectorals','anterior_deltoid'],
 'mobility', 'stretch', array['yoga_mat','foam_roller'], 'beginner', false,
 'Lie on a foam roller placed along the spine (parallel to the spine). Arms out to the sides, palms facing up. Let gravity open the chest and pull the shoulders back and down. Hold 3-5 minutes.',
 'Using too large a foam roller (makes the position unstable), not allowing full relaxation (this is a passive stretch — the effort is to stop efforting), putting the roller under the shoulder blades only (must be along the full spine for stability).',
 'mobility',
 array['Gravity is the therapist: the arms open and drop with gravity — no active effort is needed or wanted','Pec minor is the deepest chest muscle: it attaches to the coracoid process and pulls the shoulder into forward rounding when tight','3-5 minutes: the connective tissue response to sustained pressure takes time — less than 2 minutes rarely creates meaningful change','This is the antidote to the keyboard-and-screen posture: 5 minutes daily on the foam roller reverses hours of chest shortening'],
 array['Pec Minor Lacrosse Ball Release','Active Chest Opener'],
 array['Doorway Chest Stretch','Hands Behind Back Chest Opener'],
 array['mobility','pec_minor','posture','chest','daily_routine'],
 array['acute_shoulder_injuries','pectoral_tears_acute'],
 'pull', 'sagittal', false, 1, null, 240, null, true),

('IT Band and TFL Release',
 'IT_band', array['tensor_fasciae_latae','glutes'], array['IT_band','tensor_fasciae_latae'],
 'mobility', 'stretch', array['foam_roller','lacrosse_ball'], 'beginner', false,
 'Lie on one side with the foam roller under the outer thigh (just below the hip). Prop on the elbow. Roll slowly from just below the hip to just above the knee. Pause on tender spots for 30-60 seconds.',
 'Rolling the IT band directly (the IT band itself is a tendinous structure — the roller works on the tissue around it, the TFL and the lateral quads), rolling too quickly, applying maximum pressure immediately.',
 'mobility',
 array['The TFL (tensor fasciae latae) at the hip is where IT band tension originates: spend extra time here','Rolling the IT band does not stretch it (it has minimal elasticity), but it does release the surrounding musculature that creates tension','Pain level: 6-7/10 is productive. 9-10/10 is counter-productive — the body protects itself with more tension','For runners: IT band syndrome is among the most common overuse injuries — rolling 2-3 times per week as prevention is evidence-based'],
 array['Lacrosse Ball TFL Release','Dynamic IT Band Work'],
 array['Foam Roller Light Pressure','Seated IT Band Stretch'],
