('Cervical Spine Mobility Series',
 'neck', array['upper_trapezius','SCM','levator_scapulae'], array['neck','upper_trapezius'],
 'mobility', 'rotation', array['yoga_mat'], 'beginner', false,
 'Seated or standing. Gently: 1) Chin to chest and back (10 reps). 2) Ear to shoulder each side (10 reps). 3) Turn head left and right (10 reps). 4) Diagonal: chin toward armpit each side (10 reps). All movements are slow and gentle.',
 'Forcing range of motion in the cervical spine (always gentle — the cervical spine responds poorly to aggressive mobilization), rushing, performing circular rotations (avoid full cervical circles — the extension phase can compress spinal nerves).',
 'mobility',
 array['No circles: forward and back, side to side, rotation, and diagonals — but never a full circle that combines neck extension','Gentle and slow: the cervical spine has the most neurological sensitivity of any spinal region — it rewards patience and rejects force','Daily practice: the cervical spine stiffens rapidly from screen time — 5 minutes of gentle mobility daily prevents the chronic tightness that leads to headaches and shoulder pain','The SCM (sternocleidomastoid) and levator scapulae are the primary restrictors of cervical rotation: if rotation is very limited, these muscles need targeted release'],
 array['Cervical CARS','Cervical Traction Stretch'],
 array['Simple Head Turns','Gentle Chin Tucks'],
 array['mobility','neck','cervical','posture','daily_routine'],
 array['cervical_disc_herniation','cervical_stenosis','acute_whiplash','history_of_cervical_fractures'],
 'mixed', 'multi', false, 1, null, 120, 10, true),

('Quad Stretch Standing',
 'quads', array['hip_flexors','rectus_femoris'], array['quads','hip_flexors'],
 'mobility', 'stretch', array['bodyweight'], 'beginner', false,
 'Stand on one leg (hold a wall for balance if needed). Bend the other knee, bringing the heel toward the glute. Hold the ankle. Keep the knees together and the hip extended (don''t allow the hip to flex). Hold 30-60 seconds each side.',
 'Leaning forward at the hip (the hip must remain extended — leaning forward turns this into a hip flexor stretch, not a quad stretch), knees separating (must stay together at all times).',
 'mobility',
 array['Knees together: when the knees separate, the stretch comes from the hip flexors and the rectus femoris is not maximally targeted','Hip extended: stand tall, tailbone down — if the lower back arches, squeeze the glute to posteriorly tilt the pelvis','Pulling the heel toward the glute: the closer the heel gets to the glute, the greater the quad stretch','For runners and cyclists: chronic quad shortness from the repetitive hip flexion pattern — this stretch must be done daily'],
 array['Wall Assisted Deep Quad Stretch','Kneeling Quad Stretch with Hip Extension'],
 array['Seated Quad Stretch','Prone Quad Stretch'],
 array['mobility','quads','hip_flexor','runners','daily_routine'],
 array['acute_knee_injuries','patellofemoral_pain_severe','acute_quad_strain'],
 'isometric', 'sagittal', true, 2, null, 40, 10, true),

('Hamstring Nerve Flossing',
 'hamstrings', array['sciatic_nerve','calves'], array['hamstrings','calves'],
 'mobility', 'stretch', array['yoga_mat'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Lie on back. Bring one knee to the chest (90° at hip and knee). Slowly extend the knee, then flex the ankle (point the toes toward you). Hold the end position for 5 seconds. Return to bent knee position. Repeat 10 times each leg.',
 'Forcing a straight leg (if pain shoots down the leg, the nerve is under tension — reduce the extension range), rushing, not dorsiflexing the ankle at the end of the extension.',
 'mobility',
 array['This is nerve flossing for the sciatic nerve: the combination of hip flexion + knee extension + ankle dorsiflexion tensions the sciatic nerve, encouraging it to glide through the surrounding tissue','Stop at 7/10 tension: if the leg won''t straighten without pain below the knee, that is a sciatic restriction, not a hamstring restriction — these need different treatment','Nerve mobility vs muscle flexibility: stretching a tight nerve can cause transient soreness for 24 hours (normal) or worsen neurological symptoms (stop immediately if this happens)','Physiotherapy assessment: if unable to achieve 45° of knee extension without shooting pain, consult a physiotherapist'],
 array['Neural Flossing in Standing','Sciatic Nerve Mobilization Seated'],
 array['Gentle Knee to Chest Hug','Supine Hamstring Stretch with Strap'],
 array['mobility','sciatic','nerve','hamstrings','rehabilitation'],
 array['acute_disc_herniation','active_sciatica_with_shooting_pain','piriformis_syndrome_acute'],
 'pull', 'sagittal', true, 2, 10, null, 10, true),

('Adductor Rock Back',
 'inner_thighs', array['groin','hip_flexors'], array['inner_thighs','groin'],
 'mobility', 'stretch', array['yoga_mat'], 'beginner', false,
 'Start on hands and knees. Take one leg out wide to the side, toes pointing forward (not outward), knee in line with the hip. Rock the hips backward toward the heel while keeping the extended leg in its position. 10 reps each side.',
 'Turning the toes outward (must stay pointing forward to maintain the adductor line — turned-out toes change the stretch to the outer hip), rocking too far back (go to the edge of comfortable tension, not beyond).',
 'mobility',
 array['Toes pointing forward: the moment the toes turn out, the inner thigh is de-loaded and the outer hip takes over','Rock slowly: the forward and back oscillation warms the tissue and progressively opens the adductor','This is the safest adductor opener for people with hip pathology: the weight-bearing aspect is light and controllable','Used in warm-ups for any lateral or rotational sport: hockey, soccer, tennis, BJJ, wrestling'],
 array['Deep Adductor Stretch (Pancake)','Weighted Adductor Opener'],
 array['Gentle Straddle Sit','Supine Inner Thigh Stretch'],
 array['mobility','adductors','inner_thighs','warm_up','sports_specific'],
 array['acute_groin_injury','hip_replacement_within_12_weeks'],
 'isometric', 'frontal', true, 2, 10, null, 10, true),

('Calf Stretching at Wall',
 'calves', array['Achilles_tendon','soleus'], array['calves','Achilles_tendon'],
 'mobility', 'stretch', array['bodyweight','wall'], 'beginner', false,
 'Stand facing a wall. Place one foot forward with hands on the wall. Keep the back heel flat and lean toward the wall. 1) Straight back leg (gastrocnemius stretch, 30-60s). 2) Slightly bent back leg (soleus stretch, 30-60s). Switch sides.',
 'Letting the heel lift (both stretches require the heel flat on the floor), bending the front knee during the straight-leg stretch, rushing between the two versions.',
 'mobility',
 array['Two versions, two muscles: straight knee stretches gastrocnemius (crosses the knee joint), bent knee stretches soleus (does not cross the knee joint) — both are needed for complete calf flexibility','Heel stays flat: this is non-negotiable — a lifted heel completely releases the stretch','Both are needed: most people only do the straight-leg version and leave the soleus unstretched','For runners: tight calves are implicated in Achilles tendinopathy, plantar fasciitis, and ankle injuries — daily calf stretching is the most effective single prevention strategy'],
 array['Calf Stretch on Step','Single-Leg Calf Stretch Loaded'],
 array['Seated Calf Stretch','Standing Toe Raise'],
 array['mobility','calves','Achilles','runners','injury_prevention'],
 array['acute_Achilles_rupture','acute_calf_tear','ankle_injuries'],
 'isometric', 'sagittal', true, 2, null, 45, 10, true),

('Active Spinal Decompression (Hang)',
 'erectors', array['lats','core','traps'], array['erectors','lats'],
 'mobility', 'stretch', array['pull_up_bar'], 'beginner', false,
 'Hang from a bar with both hands using an overhand grip. Let the body weight decompress the spine. Breathe deeply. Progress: single-arm hang to create lateral decompression. Hold 20-60 seconds per set.',
 'Tensing the shoulders (the hang only works if the shoulder girdle is relaxed — the weight must hang through a passive structure), shortening the session (minimum 30 seconds for meaningful disc decompression).',
 'mobility',
 array['Passive hang: let gravity do the work. The shoulders should feel like they''re being gently pulled away from the ears.','Breathe slowly and deeply: the spinal decompression is enhanced by the diaphragm drop on inhale and the intra-abdominal pressure change on exhale','After any heavy spinal loading (deadlifts, squats, overhead press), a 60-second dead hang decompresses the discs that have been compressed during the session','Daily dead hang: 5 sets of 30-60 seconds is one of the simplest and most effective spinal health habits available'],
 array['Single-Arm Hang','Jefferson Curl from Hang'],
 array['Assisted Hang with Band','Doorway Decompression'],
 array['mobility','spine_health','decompression','recovery','daily_routine'],
 array['shoulder_injuries_acute','rotator_cuff_tears_acute','wrist_injuries'],
 'pull', 'sagittal', false, 5, null, 40, 30, true),

('Split Squat Hip Flexor Mobilization',
 'hip_flexors', array['quads','glutes','groin'], array['hip_flexors','quads','glutes'],
 'mobility', 'stretch', array['yoga_mat'], 'beginner', true,
 'From a half-kneeling position (one knee down, one foot forward). Drive the hips forward into a lunge while keeping the back knee on the floor. At the end range, add a subtle hip circle (3-5 small circles). Return and repeat 8-10 times each side.',
 'Letting the front knee collapse inward (must stay over the second toe), arching the lower back (squeeze the back glute to tilt the pelvis posteriorly), making the circles too large initially.',
 'mobility',
 array['Glute squeeze on the back leg: this is the key — squeezing the back glute posteriorly tilts the pelvis, maximizing the hip flexor stretch','The circles at the end range: small, slow, controlled — this trains the hip flexor through dynamic range rather than just lengthening it statically','Dynamic vs static: the mobilization (with circles) creates greater improvement than static holding alone','10 reps before any workout: this primes the hip flexors for the explosive hip extension needed in squats, deadlifts, and running'],
 array['Half Kneeling with Arm Reach','Half Kneeling Rotation'],
 array['Standing Hip Flexor Stretch','Lying Hip Flexor Stretch'],
 array['mobility','hip_flexor','runners','warm_up','functional'],
 array['acute_knee_injuries','hip_flexor_strain_acute'],
 'isometric', 'sagittal', true, 2, 10, null, 10, true),

('Thoracic Opener with Foam Roller and Arms Overhead',
 'pectorals', array['serratus','lats','thoracic_erectors'], array['pectorals','serratus'],
 'mobility', 'extension', array['foam_roller'], 'beginner', false,
 'Place foam roller perpendicular to spine at the mid-back. Support the head. After extending back, reach both arms overhead and walk the hands further overhead with each exhale. Hold the furthest reach for 5 breaths.',
 'Not maintaining the position over the roller while reaching arms (must keep the roller as a fulcrum under the thoracic spine throughout), reaching with a shrug (arms should reach overhead without the shoulders rising).',
 'mobility',
 array['Arms overhead with the extension creates a dual stretch: thoracic extension (from the roller) + lat/serratus stretch (from the arm overhead position) simultaneously','Each exhale deepens both: the arm reaches a little further, the back extends a little more over the roller','This combination addresses the two most common restrictions in overhead athletes: thoracic extension and lat flexibility','This is the foundation exercise before any overhead pressing session: 5 minutes of this before a military press or snatch session significantly improves range and reduces injury risk'],
 array['One-Arm Overhead Thoracic Opener','Thoracic Opener with Rotation'],
 array['Foam Roller Thoracic Extension','Cat-Cow'],
 array['mobility','thoracic','overhead_mobility','pec_stretch','warm_up'],
 array['acute_thoracic_injury','wrist_injuries_that_prevent_overhead_reach'],
 'push', 'sagittal', false, 1, null, 90, 10, true),

('Piriformis Stretch Supine',
 'piriformis', array['glutes','IT_band','hip_external_rotators'], array['piriformis','glutes'],
 'mobility', 'stretch', array['yoga_mat'], 'beginner', false,
 'Lie on back with knees bent. Cross one ankle over the opposite knee. Thread one hand through the triangle of the legs and the other around the outside. Pull the bottom leg toward the chest. Hold 60-90 seconds each side.',
 'Rounding the lower back off the floor (lower back stays flat), pulling the bottom leg toward the wrong side (must pull toward the same-side shoulder, not the opposite shoulder), gripping too hard and creating tension.',
 'mobility',
 array['Pull toward the same-side shoulder: left ankle crossed over right knee → pull right leg toward left shoulder — this is the correct targeting direction','Lower back flat on the mat: any rounding brings the lumbar into the stretch and reduces piriformis targeting','The thread: one hand goes through the triangle (between the legs), one arm goes around the outside — this creates the pulling leverage','This is the most accessible piriformis stretch: suitable for everyone from post-surgical patients to elite athletes'],
 array['Supine Figure-4 with Forward Fold','Active Piriformis Strengthening'],
 array['Seated Figure-4 Stretch','Simple Knee to Chest'],
 array['mobility','piriformis','sciatic_relief','hip_external_rotation','foundation'],
 array['acute_hip_injuries','hip_replacement_within_6_weeks','acute_sciatica_with_shooting_pain'],
