('Peanut Foam Roller Lumbar Release',
 'erectors', array['QL','multifidus'], array['erectors','QL'],
 'mobility', 'stretch', array['peanut_roller','double_lacrosse_ball'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Create a peanut by taping two lacrosse balls together (or use a commercial peanut roller). Place it lengthwise along the spine. Lie back so each ball is on either side of the vertebral column, not on the spine itself. Breathe deeply. Move slowly from L5 to T12.',
 'Using a single foam roller under the lumbar spine (compresses the spinous processes — the peanut design specifically avoids this), forcing the range (this is passive release — no active effort needed or wanted).',
 'foam_rolling',
 array['The peanut design: two balls on either side of the spine, creating a channel for the spinous processes — safe for lumbar as a result','The erector spinae and QL muscles run parallel to the spine: this is where the peanut applies pressure','Breathe into the lower back: on each inhale, feel the back expand against the balls. On the exhale, let the body sink closer to the floor','5 minutes of peanut rolling after any session that loads the lower back (deadlifts, squats, Olympic lifting) reduces post-session soreness and speeds recovery'],
 array['Peanut Roller Full Spine','Active Mobility After Peanut Release'],
