('Lacrosse Ball Pec Minor Release',
 'pectorals', array['anterior_deltoid','coracobrachialis'], array['pectorals','anterior_deltoid'],
 'mobility', 'stretch', array['lacrosse_ball','wall'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Place the lacrosse ball against the wall. Stand with the ball at the pec minor location (inside the shoulder joint, below the clavicle, just medial to the shoulder). Lean into the wall, applying pressure. Roll slowly to find tender spots. Hold 60-90 seconds.',
 'Placing the ball over the shoulder joint itself (must be on the pec minor belly, below and medial to the joint — not on the joint), applying too much pressure (the shoulder area has more nerves than most body areas — start light).',
 'foam_rolling',
 array['The pec minor location: find the front of the shoulder joint, then move 3-4cm medially and 3-4cm inferiorly — this is the pec minor belly','Pins and needles = too much pressure: reduce immediately if any neurological sensation occurs — the brachial plexus is nearby','Arm movements while on the spot: slowly raise and lower the arm while maintaining lacrosse ball pressure — this creates active release (ART-style technique)','Pec minor tightness is the primary muscular cause of shoulder impingement and forward shoulder posture'],
 array['Active Pec Minor Release','Pec Minor Stretch with Lacrosse Ball'],
 array['Foam Roller Chest Opener','Doorway Chest Stretch'],
