('Foam Roller Rhomboids and Mid Traps',
 'rhomboids', array['trapezius','erectors','posterior_deltoid'], array['rhomboids','trapezius'],
 'mobility', 'stretch', array['foam_roller'], 'beginner', false,
 'Lie on the foam roller with it horizontal across the upper back at the shoulder blade level. Cross the arms across the chest (this moves the shoulder blades apart, exposing the rhomboids). Slowly roll between T4-T8, pausing on tender spots.',
 'Arms at the sides (this pushes the shoulder blades together and reduces access to the rhomboids — cross arms across the chest), rolling the neck area (must stay on the mid-back between shoulder blades and last rib).',
 'foam_rolling',
 array['Arms crossed: crossing the arms across the chest spreads the shoulder blades and gives the foam roller direct access to the rhomboids — the most important cue for this exercise','This area (the mid-back between the shoulder blades) is where most upper back stiffness originates in desk workers','Paired with thoracic extension rolling: roll the rhomboids → then roll the thoracic extension sequence for a complete upper back routine','The rhomboids are the primary postural muscles that resist forward-shoulder drift from keyboard and screen work — rolling and strengthening them is essential for desk workers'],
 array['Lacrosse Ball Rhomboids Targeted','Active Rhomboid Strengthening'],
