('Foam Roller Hip Rotators (Piriformis)',
 'piriformis', array['glutes','external_hip_rotators'], array['piriformis','glutes'],
 'mobility', 'stretch', array['foam_roller'], 'beginner', false,
 'Sit on the foam roller with one ankle crossed over the opposite knee. Lean toward the side of the crossed leg. Roll slowly around the gluteal area, pausing on tender spots for 30-60 seconds. Explore the full gluteal region.',
 'Using the figure-4 position incorrectly (the ankle must be over the knee, not the shin — foot higher than the knee), rushing past tender spots, not exploring the full gluteal map (the entire gluteal region has multiple potential tender points).',
 'foam_rolling',
 array['Figure-4 position while sitting on roller: this increases the tension of the piriformis against the foam roller, dramatically improving the release','Map the entire glute: divide the gluteal region into quadrants and systematically cover all four — the piriformis is not always in the same location in every person','Breathing is the release mechanism: the sympathetic nervous system keeps muscles tight — slow exhales encourage the myofascial release','This is the most effective tool for sciatic nerve compression from a tight piriformis: 3 minutes per side daily eliminates most piriformis-related sciatica over weeks'],
 array['Lacrosse Ball Piriformis Targeted','Active Piriformis PAILS/RAILS'],
 array['Light Foam Roller Glute','Supine Figure-4 Stretch'],
