('Foam Roller Chest (Sternum Area)',
 'pectorals', array['anterior_deltoid','intercostals'], array['pectorals'],
 'mobility', 'stretch', array['foam_roller'], 'beginner', false,
 'Place the foam roller vertically along the spine. Lie on it so the spine is supported along its length. Arms drop naturally to the sides. Breathe deeply, letting gravity open the chest. Hold 3-5 minutes.',
 'Letting the head hang without support (a folded blanket under the head maintains cervical neutrality), using too firm a roller (a softer foam roller is more comfortable for this restorative position).',
 'foam_rolling',
 array['This is both a chest opener AND a thoracic extension: the roller under the spine passively extends the thoracic while gravity opens the pectorals','Arms drop wherever they fall: some people have elbows that touch the floor; others have hands near the ceiling — wherever they fall is the correct position for their current range','3-5 minutes minimum: the connective tissue response to gravity takes time — this is a ''do nothing'' exercise that is doing everything','The best pre-workout chest opener: 5 minutes of this before a chest session improves range of motion by 10-15° immediately'],
 array['Chest Opener with Arm Raises','Active Chest Opener on Roller'],
 array['Doorway Chest Stretch','Seated Chest Opener'],
