('Lacrosse Ball Upper Trap Release',
 'trapezius', array['levator_scapulae','neck','rhomboids'], array['trapezius','neck'],
 'mobility', 'stretch', array['lacrosse_ball','wall'], 'beginner', false,
 'Place a lacrosse ball against the wall at the upper trap area (between the neck and the shoulder). Lean into the wall. Slowly move to find tender spots. Hold for 60-90 seconds. Slowly turn the head away from the ball to increase the stretch.',
 'Applying too much pressure directly on the neck (must stay on the upper trapezius muscle belly, not the cervical vertebrae), rushing to a new spot before the current spot has released.',
 'foam_rolling',
 array['The upper trap location: trace from the base of the skull, following the top of the shoulder — the upper trap runs between these two points','Head turn away from the ball: turning the head increases the neural tension and deepens the upper trap release — do this slowly and gently','Chronic upper trap tightness is almost universally caused by stress plus poor desk ergonomics: the rolling addresses the symptom, but the cause also needs to be addressed','Combine with chin tucks: after the rolling, perform 10 chin tucks (pulling the chin straight back) to strengthen the deep cervical flexors and prevent the tension from returning'],
 array['Active Upper Trap Release','Neck Traction and Release'],
 array['Light Neck and Shoulder Massage','Shoulder Rolls'],
