('Foam Roller Subscapularis Release',
 'rotator_cuff', array['deltoids','teres_major','lats'], array['rotator_cuff','deltoids'],
 'mobility', 'stretch', array['foam_roller','lacrosse_ball'], 'advanced', false,
 'Lie on your side with the foam roller or lacrosse ball placed in the armpit area (the subscapularis is accessed from the front of the shoulder blade — through the axilla). Arm reaches overhead. Hold 60-90 seconds each side.',
 'Applying too much direct pressure on the armpit lymph nodes (work around the axilla, not directly through it), using too large a roller (a lacrosse ball is more appropriate for the subscapularis — it is a small, deep muscle).',
 'foam_rolling',
 array['The subscapularis is the largest of the four rotator cuff muscles and the one most commonly tight: it creates internal rotation restriction','Through the axilla: the access point for the subscapularis is the front of the shoulder blade, accessed through the armpit area','This is an advanced technique: if unfamiliar with shoulder anatomy, work with a physiotherapist before attempting self-release here','Subscapularis release immediately improves external rotation range: test shoulder external rotation before and after — the change is usually measurable'],
 array['Active Subscapularis Release','Subscapularis PAILS/RAILS'],
