('Self-Massage Neck and Scalenes',
 'neck', array['SCM','upper_trapezius','scalenes'], array['neck','upper_trapezius'],
 'mobility', 'stretch', array['bodyweight'], 'beginner', false,
 'Using the fingers, gently massage the side of the neck along the SCM muscle. Roll the fingers into any tender areas. Hold gentle pressure for 20-30 seconds per spot. Work from the base of the skull to the clavicle. Repeat on both sides.',
 'Applying too much pressure (the neck contains carotid arteries and vagus nerve — light to moderate pressure only), pressing directly on the carotid artery (the pulse-point — always slightly posterior to the pulse).',
 'foam_rolling',
 array['Gentle only: the neck is not a body part for aggressive tissue release — work at 4-5/10 pressure maximum','Posterior to the pulse: find the carotid pulse and work just behind and around it — never directly on the artery','The scalenes are the most commonly overlooked neck muscles: they contribute to cervicogenic headaches, first rib dysfunction, and thoracic outlet syndrome','10 minutes of neck self-massage before bed reduces next-morning stiffness and headache frequency in desk workers'],
 array['Professional Massage','Neck Traction Device'],
 array['Light Neck Circles','Gentle Neck Stretches'],
