('Foam Roller Full Body Scan Protocol',
 'core', array['erectors','quads','calves','lats','glutes'], array['core','erectors','quads'],
 'mobility', 'stretch', array['foam_roller','lacrosse_ball'], 'beginner', false,
 'A complete 20-minute rolling protocol: Calves (3min) → Hamstrings (3min) → Glutes/Piriformis (2min each side) → IT Band (2min each side) → Quads (2min each side) → Upper Back/Lats (3min) → Chest (2min). Pause at each tender spot.',
 'Rushing through the protocol without pausing at tender spots, rolling only the common areas (quads and back) and skipping less-common areas (calves, peroneals, inner thighs), doing the protocol too infrequently.',
 'foam_rolling',
 array['The full scan: treat the body like a map that needs to be systematically explored — start at the feet and work up','20 minutes twice per week is the minimum for meaningful myofascial maintenance: daily is ideal for active athletes or those with significant restrictions','Tender spots are information: they indicate areas of high myofascial tension that are restricting movement and performance — they deserve extra attention, not avoidance','Post-workout vs pre-workout: pre-workout rolling uses shorter holds (30 sec) to warm and activate; post-workout rolling uses longer holds (60-90 sec) to release and recover'],
 array['Full Body Rolling with Targeted Deep Work','Sport-Specific Rolling Protocol'],
 array['Quick 10-Minute Rolling Protocol','Upper Body Rolling Only'],
