('Diaphragmatic Breathing',
 'core', array['diaphragm','intercostals','pelvic_floor'], array['core','diaphragm'],
 'yoga_pilates', 'isometric', array['yoga_mat'], 'beginner', false,
 'Lie on your back with one hand on the chest and one on the belly. Breathe in through the nose, directing the breath downward so the belly rises first and the chest rises second. Exhale slowly through the mouth. 10-15 breaths, 2-3 sets.',
 'Chest breathing only (the shoulders and chest rise first while the belly barely moves — the opposite of diaphragmatic breathing), holding the breath rather than making it rhythmic, trying too hard (effortless belly breathing is the goal).',
 'breathwork',
 array['Belly rises first: the diaphragm descends on the inhale — this is what moves the belly outward','Chest hand stays still: if the chest hand rises before the belly hand, you''re chest breathing — redirect the breath down','Exhale is longer: breathe in for 4 counts, out for 6 counts — the longer exhale activates the parasympathetic nervous system','5 minutes of diaphragmatic breathing before sleep reduces cortisol, improves sleep onset, and decreases sympathetic nervous system activity'],
 array['Diaphragmatic Breathing in Plank','Box Breathing'],
 array['Observation Breathing','Seated Diaphragmatic Breathing'],
 array['breathwork','parasympathetic','stress_relief','foundation','recovery'],
 array['severe_anxiety_that_is_worsened_by_breath_focus'],
 'isometric', 'sagittal', false, 3, null, 120, 30, true),

('Box Breathing (4-4-4-4)',
 'core', array['diaphragm','intercostals'], array['core','diaphragm'],
 'yoga_pilates', 'isometric', array['yoga_mat'], 'beginner', false,
 'Sit or lie comfortably. Inhale through the nose for 4 counts. Hold the breath for 4 counts. Exhale through the mouth for 4 counts. Hold empty for 4 counts. Repeat for 5-10 minutes.',
 'Holding the breath with tension (the hold phases must be relaxed — tension defeats the parasympathetic activation), counting too fast (4 counts should be approximately 4 seconds), hyperventilating (if light-headed, stop and breathe normally).',
 'breathwork',
 array['The four-part breath: inhale → hold → exhale → hold. Each phase equal duration. The equal-phase structure is what makes this ''box'' breathing.','Hold without tension: the breath pauses, but the body relaxes — imagine the breath suspended rather than held','Used by Navy SEALs for acute stress regulation: 5 minutes of box breathing before high-stakes situations measurably reduces cortisol and improves performance','Progress: 4-4-4-4 → 5-5-5-5 → 6-6-6-6 → as high as a comfortable 8-8-8-8 over months'],
 array['Box Breathing 6-6-6-6','Extended Box Breathing with Visualization'],
 array['Simple Diaphragmatic Breathing','4-7-8 Breathing'],
 array['breathwork','stress_regulation','parasympathetic','performance','sleep'],
 array['severe_cardiovascular_conditions','COPD_severe'],
 'isometric', 'sagittal', false, 1, null, 300, null, true),

('4-7-8 Breathing',
 'core', array['diaphragm'], array['core','diaphragm'],
 'yoga_pilates', 'isometric', array['yoga_mat'], 'beginner', false,
 'Inhale through the nose for 4 counts. Hold for 7 counts. Exhale through the mouth making a whoosh sound for 8 counts. This is one cycle. Perform 4 cycles. Best done before sleep for its powerful sedative effect.',
 'Extending the count faster than real seconds (4-7-8 at proper timing is a powerful sedative — too fast reduces its effectiveness), doing more than 4 cycles initially (this can cause lightheadedness in beginners).',
 'breathwork',
 array['The exhale must be complete: 8 counts of emptying the lungs, with a whoosh sound — the active exhale engages the parasympathetic more powerfully than a passive exhale','4 cycles only for beginners: this technique is powerful — start with 4 cycles, build to 8 over months','Dr. Andrew Weil describes this as a ''natural tranquilizer for the nervous system'': regular practice changes the resting HRV over weeks','Best use: in bed before sleep, or during acute anxiety moments — it works within 2-3 cycles in most people'],
 array['4-7-8 Extended Practice','Pranayama Series'],
 array['Box Breathing','Simple Belly Breathing'],
 array['breathwork','sleep','anxiety_relief','parasympathetic','evidence_based'],
 array['pregnancy','severe_anxiety_breath_worsened','COPD_severe'],
 'isometric', 'sagittal', false, 1, 4, null, null, true),

('Alternate Nostril Breathing (Nadi Shodhana)',
 'core', array['diaphragm','sinuses'], array['core','diaphragm'],
 'yoga_pilates', 'isometric', array['yoga_mat'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Sit tall. Use the right hand: close the right nostril with the thumb, inhale left. Close both (thumb and ring finger), hold. Release the thumb, exhale right. Inhale right. Close both, hold. Exhale left. This is one cycle. 5-10 cycles.',
 'Rushing the breath (this is a slow, deliberate practice — a minimum of 4-6 counts for each phase), tensing the hand and face (only the fingers on the nose need to move — everything else relaxes).',
 'breathwork',
 array['Right hand mudra: use the Vishnu mudra — index and middle fingers fold down, thumb closes right nostril, ring and pinky close left nostril','Equal breath in each nostril: the alternating pattern is the technique — don''t favor one nostril over the other','Scientific evidence: nadi shodhana measurably reduces blood pressure and anxiety within one session of 10 minutes, according to multiple clinical trials','The ancient yogic claim: this practice ''balances the two hemispheres of the brain'' — modern neuroscience shows it does modulate hemispheric activity'],
 array['Nadi Shodhana with Ratio Breathing','Extended Pranayama Practice'],
 array['Simple Diaphragmatic Breathing','Alternate Nostril Simple Version'],
 array['breathwork','pranayama','anxiety_relief','blood_pressure','meditation'],
 array['acute_respiratory_infections','severe_nasal_blockage','COPD_severe'],
 'isometric', 'sagittal', false, 1, 10, null, null, true),

('Wim Hof Breathing Method',
 'core', array['diaphragm','cardiovascular_system'], array['core','diaphragm'],
 'yoga_pilates', 'isometric', array['yoga_mat'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Lie down. Take 30 powerful inhales through the mouth (belly-to-chest expansion). After the 30th exhale, hold the breath out as long as comfortable. Inhale fully, hold for 15 seconds, exhale. This is one round. Perform 3 rounds.',
 'Doing this while driving or in water (dizziness and unconsciousness are possible — always practice lying down in a safe environment), hyperventilating to the point of tingling (some tingling is normal — unconsciousness is not — stop if feeling faint).',
 'breathwork',
 array['NEVER practice near water or while operating vehicles: the breathholding phase can cause involuntary loss of consciousness','30 power breaths: active inhale, passive exhale — the hyperventilation is deliberate and controlled','The breath hold after exhale: this is where the immune and metabolic effects occur — research shows measurable immune response changes','Developed by Wim Hof (Iceman): this technique has been studied at universities for its effects on inflammation, immune function, and cold tolerance'],
 array['Wim Hof with Cold Exposure','Extended Wim Hof Three Rounds'],
 array['Simple Diaphragmatic Breathing','Box Breathing'],
 array['breathwork','cold_therapy','immune_system','inflammation','performance'],
 array['pregnancy','epilepsy','cardiovascular_disease','high_blood_pressure','respiratory_conditions','mental_health_conditions_with_dissociation_risk'],
 'isometric', 'sagittal', false, 3, null, 300, 60, true),

('Body Scan Meditation',
 'core', array[], array['core'],
 'yoga_pilates', 'isometric', array['yoga_mat'], 'beginner', false,
 'Lie in savasana. Close the eyes. Bring attention systematically from the toes, up through the feet, ankles, calves, knees, thighs, hips, lower back, abdomen, chest, fingers, hands, arms, shoulders, neck, face, and crown. At each body part, breathe into it and release.',
 'Rushing through body parts (each area deserves 20-30 seconds of attention — a full body scan takes 15-20 minutes), judging sensations as good or bad (observe without judgment — note what is there and move on), falling asleep and waking up with no memory of the scan.',
 'breathwork',
 array['Observe, don''t judge: the meditation instruction is to notice what is there — tension, pain, warmth — without labeling it as a problem','Breathe into each area: this is not literal, but intentional: direct the attention and intention of the breath to each body part','The body scan is the foundation of MBSR (Mindfulness-Based Stress Reduction): Jon Kabat-Zinn''s clinical protocol includes this as the primary practice','Research: regular body scan practice reduces chronic pain perception, reduces anxiety, and improves sleep quality across multiple clinical populations'],
 array['Extended Body Scan with Visualization','Yoga Nidra Full Practice'],
 array['Simple 5-Minute Body Scan','Progressive Muscle Relaxation'],
 array['breathwork','meditation','mindfulness','MBSR','recovery'],
 array[],
 'isometric', 'sagittal', false, 1, null, 1200, null, true),

('Yoga Nidra (Yogic Sleep)',
 'core', array[], array['core'],
 'yoga_pilates', 'isometric', array['yoga_mat'], 'beginner', false,
 'Lie in savasana. Follow a guided yoga nidra recording (30-45 minutes). The practice cycles through relaxation, intention setting (sankalpa), body rotation awareness, breath awareness, sensation pairs (heavy/light, warm/cold), visualization, and integration.',
 'Resisting sleep when sleep comes (in yoga nidra, falling asleep is acceptable — the practice works whether or not you are fully conscious), trying to actively control the experience (the instruction is always to witness, never to control).',
 'breathwork',
 array['45 minutes of yoga nidra is reported to provide the equivalent rest of 3 hours of sleep — though this claim requires more research, the restorative effects are measurable','Sankalpa (intention): the teacher asks for a short positive intention at the beginning and end of the practice — this is planted in the subconscious during the hypnagogic state','This practice is used clinically with veterans for PTSD, with cancer patients for pain management, and in sports for recovery','The hypnagogic state (between waking and sleep) is where yoga nidra operates: this state has unique neurological properties for learning and processing'],
 array['Advanced Yoga Nidra with Visualization','Extended 60-Minute Yoga Nidra'],
 array['Simple Savasana','10-Minute Body Scan'],
 array['breathwork','yoga_nidra','recovery','sleep','PTSD_therapeutic'],
 array[],
 'isometric', 'sagittal', false, 1, null, 2700, null, true),

('Coherent Breathing (5-5)',
 'core', array['diaphragm','cardiovascular_system'], array['core','diaphragm'],
 'yoga_pilates', 'isometric', array['yoga_mat'], 'beginner', false,
 'Breathe in for exactly 5 seconds, breathe out for exactly 5 seconds. Maintain this rhythm continuously for 10-20 minutes. This rate (6 breaths per minute) synchronizes the breath with the natural oscillation of the cardiovascular system.',
 'Varying the count (the exact 5-5 rhythm is essential — even a second of variation reduces the cardiovascular resonance effect), breathing shallowly (both the inhale and exhale should be deep and full within the 5-second constraint).',
 'breathwork',
 array['6 breaths per minute is the resonant frequency of the cardiovascular system: at this rate, heart rate variability peaks — the measure of autonomic nervous system health','The Coherence breathing research: Stephen Elliott''s work and HeartMath research shows measurable improvements in HRV, blood pressure, and stress after weeks of daily practice','No specific technique required: just count 5-in, 5-out — this simplicity is why it is sustainable as a daily practice','10 minutes daily is the research dose: more time in practice shows increasing benefit, but 10 minutes already produces measurable cardiovascular effects'],
 array['Extended Coherent Breathing 20min','Coherent Breathing with HRV Biofeedback'],
 array['Simple Belly Breathing','4-4 Breathing Introduction'],
 array['breathwork','HRV','cardiovascular','evidence_based','daily_routine'],
 array['severe_cardiovascular_conditions'],
 'isometric', 'sagittal', false, 1, null, 600, null, true),

('Progressive Muscle Relaxation',
 'core', array['all_major_muscle_groups'], array['core'],
 'yoga_pilates', 'isometric', array['yoga_mat'], 'beginner', false,
 'Lie down. Starting with the feet: tense the muscles as hard as possible for 5 seconds. Release completely and notice the relaxation for 10 seconds. Proceed up the body: calves → quads → glutes → abs → chest → hands → arms → shoulders → face.',
 'Not fully releasing after each tension (the release phase is the therapeutic moment — it must be complete), tensing for too long (5 seconds is sufficient — longer causes cramping in some muscle groups), tensing without breathing.',
 'breathwork',
 array['Tense then release: the contrast between maximum tension and complete release teaches the nervous system what ''truly relaxed'' feels like','The release is the medicine: most people live in a state of partial tension they don''t notice — PMR resets this baseline','Edmund Jacobson developed PMR in the 1920s: it remains one of the most evidence-backed stress reduction techniques','Uses: insomnia, chronic pain, generalized anxiety disorder, hypertension — research consistently shows PMR reduces physiological stress markers'],
 array['PMR with Visualization','Advanced PMR with Breath Integration'],
 array['Body Scan Meditation','Simple Relaxation Breathing'],
