('Physiological Sigh (Stress Relief Breath)',
 'core', array['diaphragm','intercostals'], array['core','diaphragm'],
 'yoga_pilates', 'isometric', array['bodyweight'], 'beginner', false,
 'Take a normal inhale through the nose. At the top of the inhale, take a second short sniff to maximally inflate the lungs. Then exhale fully and slowly through the mouth until the lungs are empty. Repeat 1-3 times.',
 'Exhaling too quickly (the long, slow exhale is the key — it is the exhale that activates the parasympathetic response), using this as a sustained practice (it works best as an in-the-moment stress relief tool — 1-3 breaths as needed).',
 'breathwork',
 array['Double inhale: one inhale + sniff at the top — this opens the alveoli (tiny air sacs) that close during chronic shallow breathing','The long exhale: slower than feels natural — 8-10 counts is ideal — this is what produces the immediate calming effect','Andrew Huberman (Stanford) research: the physiological sigh is the fastest way to reduce acute stress — the effect is measurable within one breath','Use it anywhere: before a difficult conversation, during a stressful moment, before stepping up to compete — it takes 20 seconds and works immediately'],
 array['Extended Physiological Sigh Practice','Physiological Sigh Before Performance'],
 array['Box Breathing','Simple Deep Breath'],
 array['breathwork','acute_stress_relief','performance','evidence_based','practical'],
 array['respiratory_conditions_that_limit_deep_breathing'],
 'isometric', 'sagittal', false, 1, 3, null, null, true),

('Kapalbhati Pranayama',
 'core', array['diaphragm','rectus_abdominis'], array['core','diaphragm'],
 'yoga_pilates', 'isometric', array['yoga_mat'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Sit tall in a comfortable position. Take a normal inhale. Then rapidly and forcefully exhale through the nose by pulling the navel sharply toward the spine. The inhale is passive and automatic. Perform 30-50 pumps per minute for 2-3 minutes.',
 'Forcing the inhale (the inhale must be completely passive — only the exhale is active), hunching the spine (the spine must remain tall for the diaphragm to pump effectively), pushing through dizziness (stop and breathe normally if dizzy).',
 'breathwork',
 array['The exhale is active, the inhale is passive: this is the opposite of most breathing exercises — the forceful exhale creates the space that allows the passive inhale','The belly pumps in with each exhale: imagine the navel pressing sharply toward the spine on every exhale','Gradual build: 20 pumps then pause and breathe normally × 3 sets is the correct beginner approach, not continuous practice','Traditional yogic claim: kapalbhati ''cleanses the skull'' (kapala = skull, bhati = to shine) through its activation of the respiratory and nervous system'],
 array['Kapalabhati Advanced Rapid','Bhastrika Pranayama'],
 array['Simple Diaphragmatic Breathing','Breath Awareness Meditation'],
 array['breathwork','pranayama','energizing','digestion','yoga'],
 array['pregnancy','high_blood_pressure_uncontrolled','epilepsy','hernia','cardiac_conditions'],
 'isometric', 'sagittal', false, 3, null, 120, 30, true),

('Ujjayi Breath (Ocean Breath)',
 'core', array['diaphragm','throat'], array['core','diaphragm'],
 'yoga_pilates', 'isometric', array['yoga_mat'], 'beginner', false,
 'Breathe in and out through the nose. Slightly constrict the back of the throat as if fogging a mirror but with the mouth closed. This creates a soft ocean-wave sound. Maintain this breath throughout an entire yoga practice.',
 'Opening the mouth (ujjayi is practiced with the mouth closed throughout), constricting so hard that the breath becomes labored (the sound should be soft and effortless — not a struggle), dropping the ujjayi breath when poses become challenging (that is exactly when to maintain it most carefully).',
 'breathwork',
 array['The ocean sound: imagine breathing through a small straw at the back of the throat — the sound this creates is the ujjayi sound','Maintain throughout: the ujjayi breath is the thread that connects every moment of a yoga practice — when it stops, the mind wanders','This breath naturally extends the exhale slightly: this is why yoga practitioners look calmer — the nervous system is being continually regulated by the extended exhale','Ujjayi creates internal heat (tapas): in a cold yoga studio, this breath warms the body from within'],
 array['Ujjayi in Challenging Poses','Extended Ujjayi in Advanced Sequence'],
 array['Simple Nose Breathing','Mouth Breathing Practice'],
 array['breathwork','pranayama','yoga','heat_building','meditative'],
 array['throat_injuries_acute','severe_nasal_congestion'],
 'isometric', 'sagittal', false, 1, null, 600, null, true),

('Bhramari Pranayama (Humming Bee Breath)',
 'core', array['diaphragm','vocal_cords','sinus'], array['core','diaphragm'],
 'yoga_pilates', 'isometric', array['yoga_mat'], 'beginner', false,
 'Sit tall. Close the eyes. Place index fingers gently on the tragus of each ear (the flap of cartilage). Inhale deeply through the nose. On the exhale, make a steady humming sound like a bee. Feel the vibration in the face and skull. 10-15 breaths.',
 'Making the humming sound with the mouth open (lips must stay closed — the vibration must occur internally), humming at too high a pitch (a lower pitch creates deeper internal resonance and a more pronounced vagal response).',
 'breathwork',
 array['The vibration is therapeutic: the humming creates vibration in the vagus nerve (which passes through the throat) — this directly activates the parasympathetic nervous system','Ears closed: blocking the ears with the index fingers turns the attention fully inward — this is a sensory withdrawal practice (pratyahara)','Research: bhramari pranayama measurably increases nitric oxide production in the sinuses — nitric oxide has antiviral, anti-inflammatory, and vasodilatory properties','This is the most effective single breath practice for acute anxiety management: 5 minutes measurably reduces sympathetic activation'],
 array['Extended Bhramari 20 Breaths','Bhramari with Shanmukhi Mudra'],
 array['Simple Humming on Exhale','Basic Breathing with Elongated Exhale'],
 array['breathwork','pranayama','anxiety_relief','vagus_nerve','evidence_based'],
 array['acute_ear_infections','tinnitus_severe','throat_injuries'],
 'isometric', 'sagittal', false, 1, 15, null, null, true),

('Mindful Walking',
 'quads', array['calves','glutes','core'], array['quads','calves','glutes'],
 'yoga_pilates', 'locomotion', array['bodyweight'], 'beginner', true,
 'Walk at a deliberately slow pace (slower than normal walking). Notice the sensation of each foot contacting the floor. Feel the transfer of weight from heel to ball. Notice the leg lifting and swinging. Breath stays natural. 10-20 minutes.',
 'Trying to walk in rhythm with the breath (this creates mental calculation and removes mindfulness), walking at normal speed (the slow pace is deliberate — it allows the mind to track each movement component), thinking about the destination rather than the steps.',
 'breathwork',
 array['Each step as a complete event: heel contact → weight transfer → ball of foot → push off → lift → swing — follow each phase with full attention','The mind will wander: when it does, gently return attention to the foot. This is the practice — not the periods of attention, but the returning to attention.','Thich Nhat Hanh: ''Walk as if you are kissing the Earth with your feet'' — this cue changes the entire quality of mindful walking','Research: 20 minutes of mindful walking reduces cortisol by a measurable amount, comparable to seated meditation in stress reduction'],
 array['Mindful Walking in Nature (Shinrin-yoku)','Mindful Walking with Gratitude Practice'],
 array['Mindful Breathing Seated','Simple Walking'],
 array['breathwork','mindfulness','walking','stress_reduction','daily_routine'],
 array[],
 'mixed', 'sagittal', false, 1, null, 1200, null, true),

('Cold Exposure Breath Preparation',
 'core', array['diaphragm','cardiovascular_system'], array['core','diaphragm'],
 'yoga_pilates', 'isometric', array['yoga_mat'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Before cold water exposure (cold shower, ice bath, cold plunge): perform 3 rounds of 30 power breaths followed by breath holds. This pre-loading creates elevated oxygenation and mental readiness for the physiological stress of cold.',
 'Practicing near water (dizziness is possible — always on land before the cold exposure), skipping the breathwork and going straight to cold (the preparation significantly reduces the perception of cold and prevents the panic response).',
 'breathwork',
 array['Breathwork before cold: the hyperventilation phase raises blood oxygen and mental focus, making the initial cold shock manageable rather than overwhelming','The goal of the breathwork is readiness: physical (higher blood oxygen, alkaline pH) and mental (parasympathetic control established before the challenge)','Progress: shower → cold shower finish → cold plunge — always do the breathwork before each type of cold exposure','Research: breathwork before cold exposure increases tolerance duration and reduces cardiovascular stress responses compared to cold without breathwork'],
 array['Full Cold Plunge Protocol','Ice Bath Recovery Session'],
 array['Basic Diaphragmatic Breathing','Wim Hof Breathing'],
 array['breathwork','cold_therapy','performance','stress_inoculation','recovery'],
 array['cardiovascular_disease','Raynaud''s_disease','pregnancy','epilepsy'],
 'isometric', 'sagittal', false, 3, null, 300, 60, true),

('Nadi Shodhana Extended (Full Kumbhaka)',
 'core', array['diaphragm'], array['core','diaphragm'],
 'yoga_pilates', 'isometric', array['yoga_mat'], 'advanced', false,
 'Advanced alternate nostril breathing with breath retention (kumbhaka): Inhale left for 4 counts → Hold both nostrils for 16 counts → Exhale right for 8 counts → Inhale right for 4 counts → Hold for 16 counts → Exhale left for 8 counts. This is a 1:4:2 ratio.',
 'Attempting extended breath holds without first establishing the 1:1:2 basic ratio for several months, tensing the body during the holds, practicing on a full stomach.',
 'breathwork',
 array['The 1:4:2 ratio is the classic pranayama ratio: inhale 4, hold 16, exhale 8 — the hold is 4× the inhale, the exhale is 2× the inhale','This ratio is called antara kumbhaka (internal retention) and bahya kumbhaka (external retention) in the yogic tradition','Prerequisites: this practice requires a stable foundation in basic nadi shodhana and diaphragmatic breathing — months, not days','The science: breath retention (kumbhaka) stimulates the carotid chemoreceptors, which are highly connected to autonomic nervous system regulation — longer holds create deeper vagal tone'],
 array['Advanced Kumbhaka Ratios (1:4:2 Extended)','Full Classical Pranayama Practice'],
 array['Basic Nadi Shodhana','Box Breathing'],
 array['breathwork','pranayama','advanced','kumbhaka','nervous_system'],
 array['cardiovascular_disease','hypertension','pregnancy','epilepsy','respiratory_conditions'],
 'isometric', 'sagittal', false, 1, 5, null, null, true),

('Morning Breath Practice',
 'core', array['diaphragm'], array['core','diaphragm'],
 'yoga_pilates', 'isometric', array['yoga_mat'], 'beginner', false,
 'A 10-minute morning sequence: 3 minutes diaphragmatic breathing → 3 minutes box breathing (4-4-4-4) → 3 minutes coherent breathing (5-5) → 1 minute physiological sigh × 3. Sets the nervous system tone for the entire day.',
 'Skipping this practice when time is limited (even just the first 3 minutes provides measurable benefit — partial practice is better than no practice), practicing immediately after waking without first drinking water (hydration first).',
 'breathwork',
 array['The 10-minute investment: research shows that a consistent morning breath practice changes the baseline HRV (heart rate variability) within 4-6 weeks of daily practice','Sequence matters: diaphragmatic first (warms the system) → box (regulates) → coherent (resonates) → sigh (releases) — each builds on the last','Water first: drink 500ml of water before practicing — mild dehydration from overnight sleep significantly affects breath quality and mental clarity','This practice is the single most effective nervous system regulation habit: more research-backed than cold exposure, journaling, or meditation alone'],
 array['Extended Morning Breathwork 20min','Advanced Pranayama Morning Sequence'],
 array['Single Breathwork Technique','5-Minute Breath Observation'],
 array['breathwork','morning_routine','HRV','daily_routine','evidence_based'],
 array['severe_respiratory_conditions'],
 'isometric', 'sagittal', false, 1, null, 600, null, true),

('Sleep Breathing Protocol',
 'core', array['diaphragm'], array['core','diaphragm'],
 'yoga_pilates', 'isometric', array['yoga_mat'], 'beginner', false,
 'Lying in bed: 5 minutes 4-7-8 breathing → 5 minutes progressive muscle relaxation → body scan until asleep. This sequence systematically shuts down the sympathetic nervous system to facilitate sleep onset.',
 'Trying this while checking the phone between techniques (any blue light exposure or mental stimulation defeats the parasympathetic activation), being impatient when sleep doesn''t come immediately (some nights require the full sequence twice — that is normal).',
 'breathwork',
 array['Sequence: 4-7-8 lowers arousal → PMR removes residual muscle tension → body scan transitions to sleep — each step addresses a different barrier to sleep onset','This protocol is based on the same mechanisms as evidence-based CBT-I (Cognitive Behavioral Therapy for Insomnia)','Most sleep problems are hyperarousal problems: the nervous system is still in ''on'' mode when it needs to switch to ''off'' — this sequence creates the switch','Average time to sleep onset should decrease from weeks to months of practice: the protocol trains the nervous system that lying down = sleep time'],
 array['Extended Sleep Protocol with Visualization','Advanced Yoga Nidra for Sleep'],
 array['4-7-8 Breathing Only','Simple Progressive Muscle Relaxation'],
 array['breathwork','sleep','insomnia','CBT_I','evidence_based'],
 array[],
 'isometric', 'sagittal', false, 1, null, 1200, null, true),

('Pre-Competition Breath Routine',
 'core', array['diaphragm','cardiovascular_system'], array['core','diaphragm'],
 'yoga_pilates', 'isometric', array['bodyweight'], 'intermediate', false,
 '10 minutes before competition or performance: 2 minutes power breathing (Wim Hof style, energizing) → 2 minutes box breathing (calming/stabilizing) → 2 minutes visualization with coherent breath → 2 minutes physiological sighs → 2 minutes natural breath observation.',
 'Using only calming breathwork before competition (some athletes need energizing before others need calming — this sequence provides both and lets the body find its optimal state), practicing for the first time immediately before competition (must be practiced in training first).',
 'breathwork',
 array['The sequence addresses two opposite needs: energy (Wim Hof) and calm (box breathing) — elite performers need both','Personalization: some athletes will stay longer in the energizing phase; others in the calming phase — use this template, then adapt based on experience','Practice this in training for weeks before using in competition: the nervous system responses are trainable, but they need repetition to become automatic','Used by Olympic athletes, professional sports teams, and military special forces: breath regulation before performance is now standard sports science practice'],
 array['Advanced Pre-Competition Visualization Protocol','Sport-Specific Breath Training'],
 array['Simple Box Breathing','Basic Competition Breathing'],
 array['breathwork','performance','competition','sports_science','nervous_system'],
 array['severe_cardiovascular_conditions','respiratory_conditions'],
 'isometric', 'sagittal', false, 1, null, 600, null, true),

('Evening Wind-Down Breath',
 'core', array['diaphragm'], array['core','diaphragm'],
 'yoga_pilates', 'isometric', array['yoga_mat'], 'beginner', false,
 'Sit or lie comfortably 30-60 minutes before bed. Breathe in for 4 counts through the nose, out for 8 counts through the mouth (making a soft ''haaa'' sound). The double-length exhale is the parasympathetic key. 15-20 breaths.',
 'Practicing too close to bed (needs 30-60 minutes before sleep — combined with phone time defeats the benefit), using a short exhale (the exhale must be at least twice the inhale length to achieve the parasympathetic effect).',
 'breathwork',
 array['Exhale twice as long as inhale: this is the simplest and most universal breathwork rule for parasympathetic activation','The ''haaa'' exhale: the soft vocalized sound creates slight glottis constriction (like ujjayi without the nose) that extends the exhale naturally','30-60 minutes before bed: enough time for cortisol to continue dropping before sleep attempts — too late and it merely delays the fight to sleep','This single practice, done consistently for 30 days, measurably improves sleep quality scores (PSQI) in research populations'],
 array['Extended Evening Breathwork','4-7-8 Breathing Sequence'],
 array['Simple Deep Breaths Before Sleep','Gentle Body Scan'],
 array['breathwork','sleep','evening_routine','parasympathetic','evidence_based'],
 array[],
