('PNF Hamstring Stretch',
 'hamstrings', array['glutes','calves'], array['hamstrings','glutes'],
 'mobility', 'stretch', array['yoga_mat','resistance_bands'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Lie on back. Raise one leg as high as possible, using a strap or partner for support. Contract the hamstring isometrically (push against the strap) for 7 seconds at maximum effort. Relax completely. Allow the leg to move further into range. Repeat 3 times.',
 'Not contracting maximally in the isometric phase (6-7 seconds of maximum effort creates the autogenic inhibition that makes the subsequent stretch more effective), rushing the contraction-to-stretch transition, giving up after one cycle.',
 'stretching',
 array['The magic of PNF: the maximum contraction followed by relaxation sends a signal to the Golgi tendon organ that releases the muscle''s protective shortening — this is why PNF gains are 2-3× greater than static stretching alone','Contract maximally: 7 seconds of genuine maximum isometric force, then completely release','Wait for the release: after the contraction, wait 2 seconds before moving deeper — the Golgi tendon organ needs a moment to override the stretch reflex','PNF (Proprioceptive Neuromuscular Facilitation) was developed in rehabilitation: it remains the most effective method for rapid flexibility improvement'],
 array['Advanced PNF Contract-Relax-Contract','PNF Full Series Lower Body'],
 array['Static Hamstring Stretch','Strap Hamstring Stretch'],
 array['stretching','PNF','hamstrings','flexibility_gains','evidence_based'],
 array['acute_hamstring_tear','hamstring_proximal_tendinopathy_acute'],
 'isometric', 'sagittal', true, 3, 3, null, 30, true),

('PNF Hip Flexor Stretch',
 'hip_flexors', array['quads','rectus_femoris'], array['hip_flexors','quads'],
 'mobility', 'stretch', array['yoga_mat'], 'intermediate', false,
 'From a half-kneeling position. Contract the hip flexor isometrically (push the back knee into the floor) for 7 seconds. Relax and drive the hip forward deeper into the stretch. Hold the new range for 20-30 seconds. Repeat 3 cycles each side.',
 'Not positioning correctly (the back knee must be on the floor, front foot forward, spine tall — the half-kneeling position must be set up correctly before the PNF begins), contracting the hip extension instead of hip flexion.',
 'stretching',
 array['Contract-relax-stretch: this is the sequence. Contraction (knee into floor = hip flexor contraction), then full relaxation, then deeper stretch — this cycle is PNF','Glute squeeze after each contraction: squeezing the back glute helps drive the hip forward into the new range — the two cues work together','3 cycles gets you to the third-cycle range: by the third cycle, most people are 15-20° further into hip extension than they could access through static stretching alone','Best time: post-workout, when the muscle tissue is warm and blood flow is high — PNF on cold muscles is less effective and carries higher injury risk'],
 array['PNF Hip Flexor with Thoracic Rotation','Advanced PNF Lower Body Series'],
 array['Static Hip Flexor Lunge Stretch','Couch Stretch'],
 array['stretching','PNF','hip_flexor','runners','evidence_based'],
 array['acute_hip_flexor_strain','hip_replacement_within_12_weeks'],
 'isometric', 'sagittal', true, 3, 3, null, 30, true),

('Doorway Hip Flexor Stretch',
 'hip_flexors', array['rectus_femoris','quads'], array['hip_flexors','quads'],
 'mobility', 'stretch', array['bodyweight','doorway'], 'beginner', false,
 'Stand in a doorway. Place one foot back, leg straight. Press the back of the rear foot against the door frame. Shift the weight forward, maintaining an upright torso. The combination of foot pressure and forward weight shift stretches the hip flexor. Hold 45-60 seconds.',
 'Allowing the lower back to arch (must maintain a neutral pelvis — the glute of the rear leg should be engaged), leaning too far forward instead of staying upright, not using the doorframe for the foot pressure.',
 'stretching',
 array['Rear foot presses into door frame: this creates an isometric contraction of the hip flexor, which triggers a reflexive release — not the same as PNF but similar mechanism','Upright torso: the stretch only works in the hip flexors if the trunk stays vertical — leaning forward moves the stretch to the lower back','Glute squeeze: engaging the glute of the rear leg posteriorly tilts the pelvis, which is the direct way to lengthen the hip flexors','No doorway? Use a wall: the foot presses flat against the wall with the knee slightly bent — same cue, same effect'],
 array['Doorway Hip Flexor with Arm Reach','Progressive Hip Flexor PNF'],
 array['Simple Standing Hip Flexor Stretch','Lunge Hip Flexor Hold'],
 array['stretching','hip_flexor','functional','no_equipment','runners'],
 array['acute_hip_flexor_strain','knee_injuries_that_prevent_the_position'],
 'isometric', 'sagittal', true, 2, null, 50, 15, true),

('Seated Piriformis Stretch',
 'piriformis', array['glutes','external_hip_rotators'], array['piriformis','glutes'],
 'mobility', 'stretch', array['yoga_mat','chair'], 'beginner', false,
 'Sit in a chair or on the floor. Cross one ankle over the opposite knee. Sit tall and gently lean forward from the hips (not the waist) until a deep stretch is felt in the outer glute of the crossed leg. Hold 60-90 seconds each side.',
 'Rounding the spine to lean forward (hip hinge forward, not spinal flexion — a rounded back takes the stretch off the piriformis and onto the lower back), not sitting tall before leaning (the first instruction is to grow tall, then lean).',
 'stretching',
 array['Hip hinge forward: lean forward by hinging at the hip crease — not by rounding the spine forward','The stretch should be felt in the outer glute of the crossed leg: if it''s felt in the lower back, round less and hinge more from the hip','A folded blanket under the seated hip helps if the hip is significantly higher than the other: equalize the hip heights before starting','This is the most popular sciatic nerve relief stretch — for piriformis-origin sciatica, 3 minutes per side daily produces measurable improvement in 2-4 weeks'],
 array['Seated Piriformis with Forward Fold','Supine Pigeon Pose'],
 array['Gentle Seated Hip Cross','Supine Knee Hug'],
 array['stretching','piriformis','sciatic_relief','seated','daily_routine'],
 array['hip_replacement_recent','acute_piriformis_syndrome_severe'],
 'isometric', 'multi', true, 2, null, 75, 15, true),

('Supine Spinal Twist',
 'erectors', array['obliques','IT_band','gluteus_medius'], array['erectors','obliques'],
 'mobility', 'stretch', array['yoga_mat'], 'beginner', false,
 'Lie on your back. Draw both knees to the chest. Lower both knees to one side. Extend the arms to a T-shape. Look in the opposite direction. Hold 60-90 seconds. Return through center and switch sides.',
 'Letting both shoulders lift off the floor (the shoulder on the opposite side of the lowered knees must stay grounded), forcing the knees to the floor (let gravity do the work over time), holding the breath.',
 'stretching',
 array['Shoulder anchored: the opposite shoulder from the knees must stay down — this creates the full-length spinal rotation, not just a hip rotation','Knees together: both knees stay touching — if they separate, the torque on the sacroiliac joint increases beyond comfortable','Let it breathe: each exhale allows the knees a tiny bit lower — hold still and breathe rather than pulling the knees down','This is one of the best sleeping positions for restoring spinal length after a day of compression'],
 array['Extended Spinal Twist with Arm Bind','Twisted Lizard'],
 array['Simple Knee Tilt','Gentle Supine Twist'],
 array['stretching','spinal_rotation','recovery','evening_routine','daily_routine'],
 array['disc_herniation_rotation_intolerant','SI_joint_instability_severe'],
 'mixed', 'transverse', true, 2, null, 75, 15, true),

('Child''s Pose Hip Stretch',
 'hip_flexors', array['glutes','erectors','groin'], array['hip_flexors','glutes'],
 'mobility', 'stretch', array['yoga_mat'], 'beginner', false,
 'From kneeling, widen the knees beyond hip-width. Sit the hips toward the heels. Walk the hands forward and lower the forehead to the mat (or a block). Arms can be extended forward (wide-knee variation) or back alongside the body. Hold 2-5 minutes.',
 'Forcing the hips to the heels immediately (place a blanket between the hips and heels if the full range is not available), lifting the head, using a hard surface without padding for the forehead.',
 'stretching',
 array['Wide knees: the wide-knee child''s pose opens the inner groin and hips simultaneously — the narrow-knee version is less effective for hip opening','Hips to heels: gravity assists — each exhale allows the hips to sink a little closer to the heels','This is the world''s most accessible restorative pose: it can be done at any time, in any state, by almost anyone','3-5 minutes changes the experience: a 30-second child''s pose is a rest. A 3-minute child''s pose is a therapeutic intervention for the hip flexors and lower back'],
 array['Extended Child''s Pose Hold','Child''s Pose with Side Reach'],
 array['Supported Child''s Pose','Kneeling Hip Flexor Stretch'],
 array['stretching','hip_flexor','recovery','restorative','daily_routine'],
 array['severe_knee_injuries','ankle_injuries_preventing_kneeling'],
 'isometric', 'sagittal', false, 1, null, 180, 10, true),

('Doorway Shoulder Stretch',
 'pectorals', array['anterior_deltoid','biceps_long_head'], array['pectorals','anterior_deltoid'],
 'mobility', 'stretch', array['bodyweight','doorway'], 'beginner', false,
 'Stand in a doorway. Place one arm on the door frame at 90° (elbow at shoulder height). Step through and rotate the body away from the arm until a stretch is felt across the chest and front shoulder. Hold 30-60 seconds each side.',
 'Not stepping fully through the door (must rotate the body enough to feel the stretch — just placing the arm on the frame without stepping through is insufficient), placing the arm too high (above 90° creates rotator cuff impingement risk).',
 'stretching',
 array['Arm at exactly 90°: elbow at shoulder height — higher stresses the rotator cuff under stretch, lower reduces the chest stretch','Step through fully: the rotation of the body is the stretch mechanism — step until you feel it in the front of the chest and shoulder','This is the single best intervention for forward shoulder posture from desk work: 2 × 60 seconds per side daily, every day','Change the angle: try the arm at 45° (lower than shoulder) to stretch lower chest fibers, then at 135° (higher than shoulder) for upper chest — systematically address all pectoral fiber directions'],
 array['Doorway Stretch with Hip Rotation','Active Chest Opening'],
 array['Wall Chest Stretch','Seated Chest Opener'],
 array['stretching','chest','shoulder_health','posture','daily_routine'],
 array['acute_shoulder_injuries','rotator_cuff_tears_acute'],
 'pull', 'sagittal', true, 2, null, 45, 15, true),

('Levator Scapulae Neck Stretch',
 'neck', array['upper_trapezius','scalenes'], array['neck','upper_trapezius'],
 'mobility', 'stretch', array['bodyweight','chair'], 'beginner', false,
 'Sit or stand. Turn the head 45° to one side and tilt it down 45° toward the same side armpit. Place the hand on the same side on the top of the head and apply very gentle downward pressure. Hold 30-45 seconds each side.',
 'Pulling the head with force (the hand provides only light weight — never active pulling), sitting with a rounded upper back (the stretch is diminished by forward posture), turning to the wrong direction.',
 'stretching',
 array['45° turn, 45° tilt toward the armpit: the combined rotation and lateral flexion creates the diagonal that lengthens the levator scapulae specifically','The levator scapulae runs from the neck to the top inner corner of the shoulder blade: its tightness causes the chronic upper neck and shoulder tension from desk work and stress','Light pressure only: the weight of the hand is sufficient — any additional pulling is too much force for a cervical stretch','Daily practice: 30-45 seconds twice per day on each side significantly reduces cervicogenic headache frequency within 2-4 weeks'],
 array['Active Levator Scapulae Stretch with Shoulder Depression','Cervical Mobility Series'],
 array['Simple Ear-to-Shoulder Stretch','Gentle Neck Rotation'],
 array['stretching','neck','levator_scapulae','headache_prevention','daily_routine'],
 array['cervical_disc_herniation','cervical_stenosis','acute_neck_injuries'],
 'isometric', 'frontal', true, 2, null, 40, 15, true),

('Cross-Body Shoulder Stretch',
 'rear_deltoids', array['rhomboids','rotator_cuff','posterior_capsule'], array['rear_deltoids','rhomboids'],
 'mobility', 'stretch', array['bodyweight'], 'beginner', false,
 'Bring one arm straight across the chest at shoulder height. Use the opposite arm to pull it further across by holding just above the elbow. Hold 30-45 seconds each side. Maintain the shoulder down (not shrugged).',
 'Grabbing the wrist instead of just above the elbow (the elbow is the correct lever point — wrist pressure can stress the elbow joint), shrugging the shoulder (must be pressed down and away from the ear throughout).',
 'stretching',
 array['Just above the elbow: this is the single most important cue — too far down the forearm stresses the elbow, too high reduces the stretch effectiveness','Shoulder down: press the stretched shoulder down and away from the ear throughout — if it rises, the upper trap is taking over from the posterior deltoid','This stretches the posterior shoulder capsule: tightness here limits internal rotation and is implicated in the ''GIRD'' (glenohumeral internal rotation deficit) seen in overhead athletes','Post-throwing warm-down: this is THE stretch for throwing athletes (baseball, cricket, volleyball) after pitching, throwing, or serving sessions'],
