('IT Band Stretch Standing',
 'IT_band', array['TFL','glutes','peroneals'], array['IT_band','TFL'],
 'mobility', 'stretch', array['bodyweight','wall'], 'beginner', false,
 'Stand near a wall. Cross one leg behind the other. Lean the hips to the side of the crossed-behind leg. Hold the wall for balance. Feel the stretch along the outer hip and thigh. Hold 45-60 seconds each side.',
 'Bending both knees (the front leg must stay straight — bending reduces the IT band tension), not leaning the hips far enough to the side (the lateral hip push is the stretch mechanism), crossing the leg behind, not in front.',
 'stretching',
 array['Hip push to the side: the lateral movement of the hip (same side as the front leg) creates the IT band tension — without this push, there is no real IT band stretch','Leg crossed BEHIND: the leg that is stretching crosses behind the other, not in front — this is the most common error in this stretch','The IT band itself barely stretches (it is a tough fibrous band): this stretch primarily works the TFL and surrounding tissue','IT band syndrome prevention: this stretch plus glute strengthening is the evidence-based protocol for IT band syndrome management'],
