('Upper Trapezius Stretch',
 'trapezius', array['neck','levator_scapulae'], array['trapezius','neck'],
 'mobility', 'stretch', array['bodyweight','chair'], 'beginner', false,
 'Sit on one hand. Tilt the head toward the opposite shoulder. With the free hand, gently add light pressure by placing it on the top of the head. Hold 30-45 seconds each side. The hand sitting on prevents the shoulder from rising.',
 'Pulling the head with force (neck stretches must be gentle — the cervical nerve roots are sensitive), forgetting to sit on the hand (this depresses the shoulder and dramatically improves the stretch quality — essential to the technique).',
 'stretching',
 array['Sit on the hand: this is the secret ingredient — sitting on the hand of the side being stretched prevents the shoulder from rising, which is the compensation that makes the stretch ineffective','Light hand pressure only: the weight of the hand on the head is sufficient — any additional pulling is too aggressive for a cervical stretch','Both sides matter: check if one side is significantly tighter (it usually is) and spend 20% more time on the tighter side','The upper trapezius is the most chronically tight muscle in modern humans: stress, screen time, and poor ergonomics all create upper trap tension — this is the most effective direct stretch'],
 array['Upper Trap Stretch with Shoulder Depression Active','Cervical CARS'],
