('Tricep Overhead Stretch',
 'triceps', array['lats','teres_major'], array['triceps','lats'],
 'mobility', 'stretch', array['bodyweight'], 'beginner', false,
 'Raise one arm overhead, bending the elbow to place the hand behind the head. Use the opposite hand to gently hold the elbow and guide it backward. Hold 30-45 seconds each side.',
 'Pulling the elbow too aggressively (this creates elbow joint stress — guide gently), leaning to the side as the arm bends (the torso should stay upright, not lateral bending to compensate for tricep tightness).',
 'stretching',
 array['Guide, don''t pull: the opposite hand provides gentle guidance — think of it as a direction rather than a force','The elbow points toward the ceiling: the angle of the elbow determines the stretch quality — vertical elbow = maximum tricep long head stretch','This also stretches the lat and teres major: feel for a stretch along the back and side of the upper arm, not just at the back of the elbow','The tricep long head crosses the shoulder joint: this overhead position is the only way to fully stretch it — regular stretching reduces elbow extension pain from tight long head'],
 array['Tricep Stretch with Towel Assist','Active Tricep Overhead Mobility'],
 array['Standing Tricep Stretch Lower','Band-Assisted Overhead Stretch'],
