('Wrist Flexor Stretch',
 'forearms', array['wrist_extensors'], array['forearms'],
 'mobility', 'stretch', array['bodyweight'], 'beginner', false,
 'Extend one arm forward, palm facing up. Use the other hand to gently bend the wrist back (fingers pointing toward the floor). Hold 30-45 seconds. Then turn the palm down and bend the wrist back the other way (prayer position stretch). Repeat each side.',
 'Pulling too hard on the wrist (this stretch requires only very light pressure — the wrist flexors are often inflamed, and aggressive force can worsen tendinitis), not stretching both directions (wrist flexors AND extensors need to be addressed).',
 'stretching',
 array['Light pressure only: 20-30% of what feels like maximum — the wrist flexors are attached to tendons that can be irritated by excessive force','Both directions: palm up + push down (flexor stretch) AND palm down + pull down (extensor stretch) — both are needed for complete wrist health','This is the primary carpal tunnel prevention stretch: tight wrist flexors and extensors both contribute to median nerve compression','Keyboard workers: this stretch twice per day reduces injury risk. Once carpal tunnel symptoms appear, consult a physiotherapist before continuing.'],
 array['Wrist Flexor PNF Stretch','Active Wrist Mobility Series'],
