 'pectorals', array['anterior_deltoid','serratus'], array['pectorals','anterior_deltoid'],
 'mobility', 'stretch', array['bodyweight','doorway'], 'intermediate', false,
 'Perform three doorway chest stretch positions: 1) Arm at 90° (middle pec, 45 sec). 2) Arm at 120° — higher (lower pec, 45 sec). 3) Arm at 60° — lower (upper pec, 45 sec). Switch sides and repeat. This addresses all three pec fiber directions.',
 'Only performing the standard 90° position (this addresses only one of the three pectoral fiber directions — the full sequence requires all three angles), rushing between positions.',
 'stretching',
 array['Three positions, three fiber directions: the pectoralis major has three muscle fiber groups (clavicular head, sternocostal, abdominal) — each stretches best at a different arm angle','90° is the most common position: add the high and low variations to ensure complete pectoral development and flexibility','This systematic approach takes 4-5 minutes: worthwhile before any pressing session (improved shoulder range → safer pressing → more effective training)','Over time, a dedicated pectoral flexibility program changes shoulder posture more than any postural exercise can alone'],
 array['Full Chest Flexibility Protocol','Advanced Pec Stretch with Rotation'],
