('Thoracic Rotation Stretch in Seated',
 'thoracic_erectors', array['obliques','rhomboids'], array['thoracic_erectors','obliques'],
 'mobility', 'stretch', array['yoga_mat','chair'], 'beginner', false,
 'Sit tall in a chair or cross-legged. Place the right hand on the left knee. Left hand behind the head. Inhale to sit taller. Exhale to rotate left as far as comfortable. Hold 3-5 breaths. Return to center. Switch sides.',
 'Rotating from the hips and lower back (the lower body must stay still — if the knee moves under the hand, the hips have rotated), pulling the head with the hand behind it (the hand is there for awareness, not to create force).',
 'stretching',
 array['Hip anchor: the knee under the hand is your feedback point — if the knee moves, the hips have rotated. Keep it still.','Sit taller before rotating: the inhale creates the length that makes the rotation accessible — exhale into the turn','Eyes lead the thoracic spine: turn the eyes first, then the head, then the shoulders — this sequential activation maximizes the rotation range','This is the most practical office stretch: it can be done every hour at a desk chair with zero equipment to maintain thoracic rotation throughout the work day'],
 array['Advanced Seated Thoracic Rotation','Standing Rotation with Dowel'],
 array['Gentle Seated Turn','Shoulder Rolls'],
