('Hip Hinge Hamstring Stretch',
 'hamstrings', array['glutes','erectors'], array['hamstrings','glutes'],
 'mobility', 'stretch', array['bodyweight'], 'beginner', false,
 'Stand with feet hip-width. Hinge forward at the hips with a flat back until a strong hamstring stretch is felt. Place hands on thighs for support. Hold 30-60 seconds. Slowly return to standing. Repeat 3-5 times.',
 'Rounding the lower back (this stretches the spine, not the hamstrings — maintain the flat back throughout the entire range), bending the knees significantly (some soft knee is acceptable, but the primary stretch should be felt in the hamstrings, not the calves).',
 'stretching',
 array['Flat back from tailbone to skull: if someone placed a wooden board along your spine, it should be touching at three points (tailbone, mid-back, skull) throughout the hinge','The hinge angle at which the hamstring stretch is felt is the correct depth: stop there and breathe before attempting to go further','This is the safest hamstring stretch: by maintaining the hip hinge pattern and flat spine, there is no spinal loading and no risk of disc herniation that can occur with slumped forward folds','Post-deadlift cooldown: this stretch is ideal after any posterior chain session to decompress the hamstrings and lower back'],
 array['RDL Hold Stretch','Single-Leg Hinge Stretch'],
 array['Seated Hamstring Stretch','Lying Hamstring Stretch'],
