('Complete Post-Run Stretch Sequence',
 'hamstrings', array['quads','calves','hip_flexors','glutes','IT_band'], array['hamstrings','quads','calves'],
 'mobility', 'stretch', array['yoga_mat'], 'beginner', false,
 'A 12-minute sequence designed for after every run. Standing calf stretch (45s each) → Standing quad stretch (45s each) → Standing hip flexor lunge (60s each) → Supine hamstring with strap (60s each) → Supine glute stretch (60s each) → Supine twist (60s each) → Lying knee hug (60s). Total: 12 minutes.',
 'Skipping any portion of the sequence (each stretch addresses a different running-specific restriction — the sequence is designed as a complete protocol, not a menu to choose from), doing this immediately after a hard run without cooling down first.',
 'stretching',
 array['Cool down first: 5-10 minutes of easy walking before this sequence — the muscle needs blood flow, not sudden stillness','The sequence order matters: standing first (uses gravity), then lying (gravity works differently) — the ordering is deliberate','12 minutes, every run: the most common reason runners don''t stretch is time. 12 minutes is the minimum effective protocol. Build the habit by doing it before untying the shoes.','This sequence addresses all six running-specific muscle groups: calves, quads, hip flexors, hamstrings, glutes, and the IT band — the six muscles that determine running injury risk'],
 array['Extended Post-Run Protocol 20min','Post-Run Yoga Flow'],
 array['5-Minute Post-Run Stretch','Single Stretch Post-Run'],
 array['stretching','runners','post_run','protocol','injury_prevention'],
